    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-02-07T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-02-07T07:00:00-05:00" n="576"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d576">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_ISA1">ISA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_MDAP1">MDAP</gloss> Files:
                    Lot 52–26: Policy <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss> Milit Aid: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Lebanon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PLC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pinkerton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d576fn1">Repeated to Cairo, Jidda, Damascus, Amman, Baghdad,
                        and London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-02-07T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 7, 1951—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>432. Department pass Amman. General <persName corresp="#p_RBH1"
                        >Robertson</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d576fn2">Sir <persName corresp="#p_RBH1">Brian
                            Robertson</persName>, Commander in Chief of British Forces in the Middle
                        East, visited several countries of the area in February to discuss military
                        defense matters.</note> told me he had informed Lebanon Government defense
                    of <gloss target="#t_ME1">ME</gloss> is primarily British responsibility and had
                    asked whether Lebanon would grant facilities in case of war. President<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d576fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_AKB1">Bishara al-Khuri</persName>.</note> agreed to
                    full cooperation in case of war but could not admit troops during peace time
                    although he said he would accept first USSR movement into Iran or Turkey as
                    state of war without waiting for formal action by governments or <gloss
                        target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>. General <persName corresp="#p_RBH1"
                        >Robertson</persName> defined Lebanon role in preparing for war demanding it
                    provide anti-aircraft defense of Beirut and perhaps Tripoli, communication
                    facilities, and some coastal defense. He said if Lebanon would ask him for
                    equipment to fill this role he would assist in obtaining it. He told me his
                    conversations with President and <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss>
                    <note n="4" xml:id="d576fn4">
                        <persName corresp="#p_ESR1">Riad</persName> el-Solh.</note> had <pb
                        facs="1043" n="1003" xml:id="pg_1003"/> been cordial and they both
                    maintained that France should not participate in Lebanon defense plans. No
                    written agreement had been made and <persName corresp="#p_RBH1"
                        >Robertson</persName> did not ask for one.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PLC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Pinkerton</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
